In the presence of ligands, the partially filled degenerate 3\(d\) orbitals of a transition metal ion are split into two different energy levels with a small energy gap \(\Delta E\) between them. There are vacancies in the higher energy \(d\) orbitals. The promotion of an electron from the lower to the higher of these \(d\) orbitals requires the absorption of radiation in the visible spectrum with energy corresponding to the energy gap. Such a d-d transition is responsible for the colour of the complex ion. The colour observed is the complement of the colours absorbed.

